{
  "id": "q-passkey-platform-constraints",
  "question": "Which browser, relying-party, and device-sync constraints must a Stellar dApp account for when using passkeys?",
  "surface": [
    "stellarDocs.search_wallet_dapp_docs",
    "skills.stellar-dev.dapp"
  ],
  "golden": {
    "answer": "WebAuthn's web API needs a secure context, but native apps can use platform credential or passkey APIs. Credentials are scoped to an RP ID rather than an exact page URL; validate RP ID and origin, account for permitted subdomain or related-origin designs, and bind any wallet/dApp handoff challenge to the intended Stellar authorization. Apple and Google providers support synchronized passkeys, but sync versus device-bound behavior is provider-specific. Mozilla's current Sync data-type list does not list passkeys, while Firefox may delegate to an OS/provider, so 'Firefox-local' is not a valid blanket rule. Explicit recovery remains necessary.",
    "keyFacts": [
      "WebAuthn's web API requires a secure context, while native apps can use platform credential/passkey APIs.",
      "Validate RP ID and origin, qualify related-origin/subdomain designs, and bind handoff challenges to the intended Stellar authorization.",
      "Apple and Google providers support synchronized passkeys, but sync and device-bound behavior is provider-specific.",
      "Mozilla Sync does not currently list passkeys as a synchronized data type, while Firefox may delegate to an OS/provider.",
      "Cross-device uncertainty requires an explicit recovery path."
    ],
    "avoid": [
      "A passkey registered for one dApp domain is automatically valid for every unrelated domain.",
      "All browsers and devices synchronize every passkey in the same way."
    ],
    "notes": "Status-sensitive details are stated as of 2026-07-11; grade later sourced changes leniently and require dated primary evidence."
  },
